    {"source": "atman", "target": "anatman", "relation": "tension", "note": "Paradigmatic test case. Claude's inferential gap model: same phenomenology, competing inferential policies."},
    {"source": "brahman", "target": "sunyata", "relation": "structural-parallel-with-divergence", "note": "Both negate origination (ajativada/MMK 1:1). Diverge on substratum: Brahman affirmed vs. emptiness of emptiness."},
    {"source": "brahman", "target": "the-one", "relation": "structural-parallel", "note": "Both beyond predication, source of all. Differ on status of matter (mithya vs. evil)."},
    {"source": "brahman", "target": "dao", "relation": "structural-parallel", "note": "Both ineffable source of all manifestation. Differ on impersonality and processual vs. static character."},
    {"source": "brahman", "target": "wahdat-al-wujud", "relation": "structural-parallel", "note": "Both posit unity of being. Ibn Arabi's tajalli parallels Brahman's self-disclosure through maya."},
    {"source": "sunyata", "target": "wu", "relation": "apparent-parallel-high-strain", "note": "Geyi conflation. Wu is cosmogonically generative; sunyata is deconstructive. Different functions despite surface resemblance."},
    {"source": "ajativada", "target": "catuskoti", "relation": "shared-logical-structure", "note": "Gaudapada 4.22 and MMK 1:1 use identical four-fold negation. Same negation, opposite inference."},
    {"source": "witness-consciousness", "target": "atman", "relation": "claim-unit-of"},
    {"source": "turiya", "target": "the-one", "relation": "structural-parallel", "note": "Both defined by negation, both beyond self-knowledge/self-relation."},
    {"source": "pancha-kosha", "target": "zuowang", "relation": "structural-parallel", "note": "Both describe progressive stripping of identification layers. What remains after negation?"},
    {"source": "alaya-vijnana", "target": "maya", "relation": "functional-parallel", "note": "Both describe how consciousness projects phenomenal world. Alaya stores seeds; maya veils Brahman."},
    {"source": "citta-matra", "target": "maya", "relation": "structural-parallel", "note": "Both deny independent external reality. Differ on what underlies appearance (sunyata vs. Brahman)."},
    {"source": "markov-blanket", "target": "anatman", "relation": "formal-parallel", "note": "FEP: self is statistical boundary, not substance. Buddhist anatta: self is construct, not entity."},
    {"source": "markov-blanket", "target": "pancha-kosha", "relation": "formal-parallel", "note": "Precision relaxation in meditation = progressive loosening of self-model priors = sheath negation."},
    {"source": "it-from-bit", "target": "dependent-origination", "relation": "structural-parallel", "note": "Both deny pre-existing determinate reality independent of participatory acts."},
    {"source": "phi-iit", "target": "brahman", "relation": "partial-parallel", "note": "Both: consciousness is fundamental. But IIT is pluralistic (many Phi values); Vedanta is monistic."},
    {"source": "emanation", "target": "dao", "relation": "structural-parallel", "note": "DDJ Ch.42 (Dao->One->Two->Three->Many) parallels One->Nous->Soul->Matter."},
    {"source": "epistrophe", "target": "dao", "relation": "structural-parallel", "note": "DDJ Ch.40 'return is the movement of the Dao' = Neoplatonic reversion to source."},
    {"source": "fana", "target": "zuowang", "relation": "structural-parallel", "note": "Both describe dissolution of self-identity in the absolute. Different ontological frameworks."},
    {"source": "being-time", "target": "dependent-origination", "relation": "radical-extension", "note": "Dogen radicalizes DO: things don't arise IN time, the arising IS time."},
